05105nam a22007815i 9780812203608DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20152000pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979748300  a97808122036087 a10.9783/97808122036082doi  a(DE-B1597)451221  a(OCoLC)913099200  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a830.9/3532231 aTobin, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWarm Brothers :bQueer Theory and the Age of Goethe /cRobert Tobin. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Cultural Studies00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface: Panic in Weimar -- tList of Abbreviations -- t1. Queering the Eighteenth Century -- t2. Warm Signifiers: Eighteenth-Century Codes of Male-Male Desire -- t3. Jean Paul's Oriental Homosexualities -- t4. Literary Cures in Wieland and Moritz -- t5. Pederasty and Pharmaka in Goethe's Works -- t6. Performing Gender in Wilhelm Meister: Goethe on Italian Transvestites -- t7. Male Members: Ganymede, Prometheus, Faust -- t8. Thomas Mann's Queer Schiller -- t9. Lichtenberg's Queer Fragments: Sexuality and the Aphorism -- tConclusion. Made in Germany: Modern Sexuality -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn eighteenth-century Germany, the aesthetician Friedrich Wilhelm Basileus Ramdohr could write of the phenomenon of men who evoke sexual desire in other men; Johann Joachim Winckelmann could place admiration of male beauty at the center of his art criticism; and admirers and detractors alike of Frederick the Great, King of Prussia, felt constrained to comment upon the ruler's obvious preference for men over women. In German cities of the period, men identified as "warm brothers" wore broad pigtails powdered in the back, and developed a particular discourse of friendship, classicism, Orientalism, and fashion.There is much evidence, Robert D. Tobin contends, that something was happening in the semantic field around male-male desire in late eighteenth-century Germany, and that certain signs were coalescing around "a queer proto-identity." Today, we might consider a canonical author of the period such as Jean Paul a homosexual; we would probably not so identify Goethe or Schiller. But for Tobin, queer subtexts are found in the writings of all three and many others.Warm Brothers analyzes classical German writers through the lens of queer theory. Beginning with sodomitical subcultures in eighteenth-century Germany, it examines the traces of an emergent homosexuality and shows the importance of the eighteenth century for the nineteenth-century sexologists who were to provide the framework for modern conceptualizations of sexuality. One of the first books to document male-male desire in eighteenth-century German literature and culture, Warm Brothers offers a much-needed reappraisal of the classical canon and the history of sexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGerman literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHomosexuality and literature. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 0aHomosexualityzGermanyxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aGay Studies.  aGender Studies.  aLesbian Studies.  aLiterature.  aQueer Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220360840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812203608423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/co